				<input id="_1" type="checkbox">
				<div class="ACT"><br><ul><li>The LysR Homolog LrhA Promotes RpoS Degradation by Modulating Activity of the Response Regulator SprE KATHERINE E. GIBSON AND THOMAS J. SILHAVY * Department of Molecular Biology , Princeton University , Princeton , New Jersey 08544 Received 15 September 1998/Accepted 11 November 1998 Synthesis of the OmpF porin of Escherichia coli is regulated in response to environmental and growth-phase signals .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
				<label class="ACT_collapse_similarity" for="act_similarity_2">
Peterson , C. N. , Carabetta , V. J. , Chowdhury , T. , and Silhavy , T. J. ( 2006 ) LrhA regulates rpoS translation in response to the Rcs phosphorelay system in Escherichia coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23091052" target="_blank">23091052</a>]<br></label>
<input id="act_similarity_2", type="checkbox">
<div class="ACT_similar">
<li>Peterson CN , Carabetta VJ , Chowdhury T & Silhavy TJ ( 2006 ) LrhA regulates rpoS translation in response to the Rcs phosphorelay system in Escherichia coli .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=20455949" target="_blank">20455949</a>]<br></li></div>
<li>However , LrhA does not bind these or related compounds , nor does presence of such compounds affect DNA binding of LrhA ( D. Lehnen and G. Unden , unpublished results ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
<li>However , the autoregulation of LrhA does not respond signiÔ¨Åcantly to the growth-phase or the C source ( D. Lehnen and G. Unden , unpublished ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
<li>The radioactively labelled promoter DNA ( 5 nM in each lane ) was incubated in the presence of a 625-fold excess of competitor DNA with increasing concentrations of isolated His6 -- LrhA protein and subjected to non-denaturing DNA PAGE ( 5 % acrylamide ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
<li>The radioactively labelled fragment ( 5 nM in each lane ) was incubated with various concentrations of LrhA in the presence of a 625-fold excess of competitor DNA and subjected to non-denaturing DNA PAGE ( 5 % acryl-amide ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>, <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>The decrease in free DNA started in the presence of 5 nM LrhA and , at 40 -- 50 nM LrhA , only the retarded band was detectable .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
<li>The shifted band appeared already in the presence of 10 nM LrhA with an apparent KD for binding of 40 nM , suggesting high afÔ¨Ånity of the protein for the promoter .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition to the repression by YjjQ shown here , transcription initiation at the Ô¨ÇhDC promoter is known to be controlled by OmpR , CRP , RcsA-RcsB and RcsB , HfdR , DksA / ppGpp , LrhA , and MatA ( EcpR ) ( 37 , 39 , 41 -- 46 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=26078445" target="_blank">26078445</a>]<br></li>
<li>Needless to say , further efforts will be necessary to investigate the possible occurrence of complex relationships that link ScoR ( GlgS ) , indole , PurR and LrhA in the regulation of E. coli motility , surface attachment and bioÔ¨Ålm formation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=23537328" target="_blank">23537328</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , agglutination was speciÔ¨Åc for mannose-containing surface proteins and depended on the type 1 Ô¨Åmbriae , and LrhA repressed the agglutination phenotype .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since LrhA represses the synthesis of Ô¨Çagella ( Lehnen et al. , 2002 ) and type 1 Ô¨Åmbriae , the effect of LrhA on bioÔ¨Ålm formation under static growth conditions was examined .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>Under the conditions tested , inhibition of Ô¨Åmbrial adhesion by methyl-a-D-mannopyranoside reduced bioÔ¨Ålm formation even more drastically than lack of Ô¨Çagella , demonstrating the crucial role in bioÔ¨Ålm formation of type 1 Ô¨Åmbriae and of their regulation by LrhA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>In accordance with the interaction of LrhA at the top level , the factors of regulation increase with increasing levels .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since it was demonstrated previously that clpX and clpP are epistatic to sprE ( 36 ) , and our epistasis data place lrhA function upstream of sprE ; these Ô¨Ånal observations imply that LrhA acts to modulate the activity of the response-regulator SprE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since LrhA plays a role in modulating the activity of the RpoS pathway , we wanted to determine whether it functions to vary the levels of RpoS or whether LrhA acts in concert with RpoS to regulate stationary-phase development .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>LrhA does not regulate synthesis of ClpX , ClpP , or SprE .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>As with LrhA , it is not known what environmental conditions regulate PecT activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>We do not yet understand how LrhA activity is regulated ; i.e. , the molecular nature of the coinducer and how its levels Ô¨Çuctuate are unknown .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>LrhA was involved in regulating acetyl phosphate levels , we would expect a decrease in ompF9-lacZ levels due to indirect effects upon OmpR activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>Instead , our observation suggests that LrhA regulates RpoS levels independently of acetyl phosphate and that there are probably multiple inputs which modulate SprE activity .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>These include activating factors as , e.g. cAMP-CRP , H-NS and CsrA as well as repressing factors such as RcsB/A , OmpR and LrhA ( recently summarized in Pr√º√ü et al. , 2006 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=17537210" target="_blank">17537210</a>]<br></li>
<li>LrhA also controls its own expression , but unlike most LysRtype regulators , LrhA is positively autoregulated ( Lehnen et al. , 2002 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>Control of LrhA function and autoregulation The function of most LysR-type regulators is controlled by effectors ( Schell , 1993 ) ; however , the effector of LrhA and of the close homologues HexA and PecT from Erwinia is not known ( Surgey et al. , 1996 ; Harris et al. , 1998 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
<li>BioÔ¨Ålm formation was stimulated by lrhA inactivation and completely suppressed upon LrhA overproduction .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>The response of lrhA expression to the presence of LrhA was tested using a lrhA cents -- cents lacZ gene fusion in lrhA-positive and - negative backgrounds ( Table 2 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
<li>When a plasmid carrying the cloned lrhA gene was introduced into the wild type to increase the concentration of LrhA , the expression of lrhA cents -- cents lacZ increased and exceeded that of the lrhA mutant by a factor of 7.4 , suggesting that lrhA expression is under positive autoregulation by LrhA .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
<li>In the absence of LrhA , however , Ô¨ÅmE expression is decreased , leading to an elevated Ô¨Åmbrial expression in the lrhA mutant .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>The positive effect of LrhA on Ô¨ÅmE9 -- 9lacZ expression is in conÔ¨Çict with the data obtained from the DNA microarray analysis , which show an increased Ô¨ÅmE expression in the absence of LrhA ( repression factor of 6 ?	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>Activation of Ô¨ÅmE expression by LrhA leads to repression of expression of the Ô¨ÅmA operon .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>Whether LrhA directly activates Ô¨ÅmE expression , which is in contrast to the function of LrhA as a repressor for other target genes , or whether it alleviates the action of an additional repressor , remains to be elucidated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>Thus , increased expression of these genes after adaptation to acetate is not dependent on regulation by LrhA , and it remains to be shown how this regulation is mediated .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12620868" target="_blank">12620868</a>]<br></li>
<li>We expect that increased expression of chemotaxis and Ô¨Çagellum genes after adaptation to propionate similarly is not dependent on regulation by LrhA , although we did not test this notion .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12620868" target="_blank">12620868</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_DOM" for="_2"><font size="5px">LrhA protein domains</font></label>
				<input id="_2" type="checkbox">
				<div class="DOM"><br><ul><li>LrhA represses RpoS stability by affecting the function of ClpXP and the response regulator S RssB ( or SprE ) , which serves as a s recognition factor .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since LrhA is 95 % similar to PecT in the Ô¨Årst 120 amino acids , which contain the putative DNA-binding domain , and since lrhA49 : : cam phenocopies lrhA overexpression , we infer that LrhA functions as a DNA-binding protein that negatively autoregulates its own expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since LrhA has homology to the LysR-like family of transcription factors ( 3 ) , possessing a canonical helix-turn-helix DNA-binding domain , we wanted to determine whether LrhA functions to regulate the expression of sprE , clpX , or clpP and thereby to affect RpoS accumulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>LrhA was originally identiÔ¨Åed as a putative DNA-binding transcription factor based on homology to the LysR-family of proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>In addition , the C-terminal end of LrhA contains a cluster of four cysfeine and two histidine residues ( C267-Xra-H-X2-C-X , .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565112" target="_blank">7565112</a>]<br></li>
<li>Simiiarity of fhe IrhA product to reguiators of tlie LysR-family The predicted IrhA product , LrhA , consists of 305 amino acid residues and has a molar mass of 33 733 Da .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565112" target="_blank">7565112</a>]<br></li>
<li>The respective consensus sequences are well conserved in LrhA ( Fig. 7 ) and the spacing of the conseived residues within each motif is in complete accordance with the consensus motifs .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565112" target="_blank">7565112</a>]<br></li>
<li>The LrhA binding site LysR-type regulators commonly bind at consensus sites ( CTGA-N7-TCAG , most conserved residues underlined ; Schell , 1993 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
				</div></ul><br>
			<label class="collapse_EVO" for="_3"><font size="5px">LrhA evolution</font></label>
				<input id="_3" type="checkbox">
				<div class="EVO"><br><ul><li>LrhA also shows similarity ( 27 % identity ) to the transcriptional regulator CbbR of Ralstonia eutropha and Xanthobacter Ô¨Çavus .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
<li>Alternatively , LrhA might regulate the expression of metabolic enzymes , as is observed with many LysR family members ( 39 ) , the activity of which might in turn be sensed by SprE either indirectly , through a cognate histidine kinase sensor , or directly , through a small molecule phosphodonor or a phosphorylated metabolic enzyme .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>Simiiarity of fhe IrhA product to reguiators of tlie LysR family The predicted IrhA product , LrhA , consists of 305 amino acid residues and has a molar mass of 33 733 Da .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565112" target="_blank">7565112</a>]<br></li>
<li>The predicted sequence of LrhA shows close similarity to the gene regulator CfxR of Alcaligenes eutrophus ( Windhovel and Bowien , 1991 ) and other gene regulators of the LysR family ( Henikoff et ai , 1988 ; Sohell , 1993 ) ( Fig. 7 and Table 1 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565112" target="_blank">7565112</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since most of the regulators of the LysR family are located adjacent to the target genes , the region of XY ] e E coii genome beyond the \ S1 element could contain unknown target genes of LrhA ( Rudd , 1992 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565112" target="_blank">7565112</a>]<br></li>
<li>LrhA , a presumed regulafor of the LysR family , is not essential for the transoripfional regulation of nuo .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=7565112" target="_blank">7565112</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since LrhA has homology to the LysR-like family of transcription factors ( 3 ) , possessing a canonical helix-turn-helix DNA-binding domain , we wanted to determine whether LrhA functions to regulate the expression of sprE , clpX , or clpP and thereby to affect RpoS accumulation .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>LrhA was originally identiÔ¨Åed as a putative DNA-binding transcription factor based on homology to the LysR family of proteins .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>Since LrhA is 95 % similar to PecT in the Ô¨Årst 120 amino acids , which contain the putative DNA-binding domain , and since lrhA49 : : cam phenocopies lrhA overexpression , we infer that LrhA functions as a DNA-binding protein that negatively autoregulates its own expression .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=9882671" target="_blank">9882671</a>]<br></li>
<li>Interestingly , HexA , a close relative of LrhA ( > 60 % identity ) from the plant pathogen Erwinia carotovora , negatively regulates the expression of rsmB , a homologue of E. coli csrB ( Mukherjee et al. , 2000 ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=16207912" target="_blank">16207912</a>]<br></li>
<li>The LrhA protein has substantial homology to HexA from Erwinia carotovora ( 64 % identity ) and PecT from Erwinia chrysanthemi ( 61 % identity ) .	[<a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/?term=12123461" target="_blank">12123461</a>]<br></li>
